'''Louis-Joseph Faure''' (5 March 1760 &ndash; 12 June 1837) was a [[French people|French]] [[jurist]] and [[politician]] who was one of the four authors of the [[Napoleonic Code]].
He was born in [[Le Havre]] and became a [[judge]] in [[Paris]] in 1791. Later he was a deputy prosecutor of the [[Seine (d√©partement)|Seine]], and then a member of the [[Council of Five Hundred]] and later the [[Tribune|Tribunat]]. He became a member of the [[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'√âtat]] in 1807. He submitted a report on the ''Code de proc√©dure'' in 1806 and one on the ''Code p√©nal'' in 1810.
