'''Aram Sahakian''' (‘±÷Ä’°’¥ ’Ñ‚Ä§ ‘±’°’∞’°’Ø’µ’°’∂ ; born [[Kayseri]], 1884 - [[Constanta]], 1968) better known by the penname '''M. Salpi''' (’ç’°’¨’¢’´) was an Armenian writer and doctor. Sahakian served as a medical officer in the Ottoman army during the World War I, and then as resident doctor at the Armenian refugee camp in [[Port Said]], Egypt. Sahakian began collecting the stories of Armenian soldiers and refugees following the deportations and massacres of their communities.<ref> The Armenian Genocide in Literature: Perceptions of Those ... 9939822189 2012</ref> He was best known for ''Our Cross'' (Armenian: ¬´’Ñ’•÷Ä ’≠’°’π’®¬ª Mer Khachu), a collection of short stories originally printed in 1921 in Paris, subsequently published in English in Los Angeles.<ref>The Armenian Review - Volume 38 -1985 - Page 53 M. Salpi, Mer khache [Our cross]</ref> Among his other works is ''Patgamavor shunery'' (¬´’ä’°’ø’£’°’¥’°’æ’∏÷Ä ’∑’∏÷Ç’∂’•÷Ä’®¬ª 1945).
